# Sarah AI — Dry Run Guide

## Step 0 — Environment Variables

Create [backend/.env](file:///c:/Users/Admin/Desktop/HR%20Project/backend/.env) if it doesn't exist:

```env
# Required — interview won't work without these
OPENAI_API_KEY=sk-...
GROQ_API_KEY=gsk_...
ELEVENLABS_API_KEY=...

# Required — use Service Role Key (bypasses RLS)
SUPABASE_URL=https://xxxx.supabase.co
SUPABASE_SERVICE_ROLE_KEY=eyJ...   # Dashboard → Settings → API → service_role

# Optional
NEXT_PUBLIC_API_URL=http://localhost:8001
NEXT_PUBLIC_WS_URL=ws://localhost:8001
```

> [!CAUTION]
> Use the **Service Role Key**, not the `anon` key. The `anon` key will fail with RLS errors when inserting into `candidates` and `interviews`.

---

## Step 1 — Database Schema (one-time)

Run this in the Supabase **SQL Editor** before the first test:

```sql
-- Add scoring columns if they don't exist yet
ALTER TABLE interviews
  ADD COLUMN IF NOT EXISTS credibility_score   INT,
  ADD COLUMN IF NOT EXISTS credibility_level   TEXT,
  ADD COLUMN IF NOT EXISTS recommendation      TEXT,
  ADD COLUMN IF NOT EXISTS summary             TEXT,
  ADD COLUMN IF NOT EXISTS scoring_details     JSONB,
  ADD COLUMN IF NOT EXISTS detected_inconsistencies JSONB DEFAULT '[]'::jsonb;
```

---

## Step 2 — Insert Test Candidate

The `fact_contract_hash` must be computed with the exact same logic as [compute_hash()](file:///c:/Users/Admin/Desktop/HR%20Project/backend/app/core/fact_contract.py#39-52) in [fact_contract.py](file:///c:/Users/Admin/Desktop/HR%20Project/backend/app/core/fact_contract.py):
- Fields (sorted alphabetically): `candidate_id`, `expected_salary`, `has_field_experience`, `years_of_experience`
- `json.dumps(data, sort_keys=True)` → SHA-256 → first 12 hex chars

Run in **Supabase SQL Editor**:

```sql
-- Enable pgcrypto if not already enabled
CREATE EXTENSION IF NOT EXISTS pgcrypto;

-- Insert test candidate (fixed UUID so it's reproducible)
INSERT INTO candidates (
    id,
    full_name,
    phone_number,
    email,
    target_role,
    years_of_experience,
    expected_salary,
    has_field_experience,
    proximity_to_branch,
    can_start_immediately,
    academic_status,
    application_source
)
VALUES (
    'TEST-AHMAD-001',
    'Ahmad Developer',
    '+962790000001',
    'ahmad.dev@test.com',
    'baker',
    3,
    800,
    true,
    'قريب (أقل من 5 كم)',
    'نعم',
    'طالب جامعي',
    'dry_run_test'
)
ON CONFLICT (id) DO NOTHING;

-- Verify the row was inserted
SELECT id, full_name, years_of_experience, expected_salary FROM candidates
WHERE id = 'TEST-AHMAD-001';
```

> [!NOTE]
> The `fact_contract_hash` is computed **live** in Python at interview start — you don't need to store it in `candidates`. The hash is generated fresh from the DB row values each time a WebSocket session opens.

